{"title":"Curriculum Pre-training for End-to-End Speech Translation","domain":"SPEECH","seeds":[{"problem":"End-to-end speech translation encoders must simultaneously transcribe speech, extract linguistic/semantic features, and learn cross-lingual mappings, but conventional ASR-only pre-training teaches mainly transcription and leaves the encoder weak in semantics and bilingual alignment.","method":"Introduce a curriculum pre-training pipeline with increasing task difficulty: (1) an elementary ASR course with multi-task CTC + cross-entropy to learn frame/word alignments and transcription; (2) two advanced courses to inject sentence understanding and cross-lingual mapping. Training is hierarchical: the bottom N encoder blocks (e.g., 8 of 12) are optimized for ASR and source-token objectives, while the top blocks are optimized for bilingual mapping. This staged, layer-partitioned pre-training strengthens encoder representations and yields consistent BLEU gains on LibriSpeech En–Fr and IWSLT En–De."},{"problem":"ASR pre-training alone does not endow the encoder with explicit sentence-level understanding of the source utterance beyond surface transcription.","method":"Propose a Frame-based Masked Language Model (FMLM) for speech: use forced alignment to locate word-level time spans, randomly mask 15% of whole-word speech segments (filled with the utterance mean), and have the encoder predict the masked source word distribution from the average hidden states over the masked span. The loss is a KL-divergence to a target distribution over source BPE tokens and is computed at the N-th encoder layer (shared with ASR), explicitly training source-language understanding in the encoder."},{"problem":"End-to-end ST encoders lack explicit supervision to map source speech segments to target-language words, forcing the decoder to learn most of the cross-lingual alignment.","method":"Introduce Frame-based Bilingual Lexicon Translation (FBLT): for each speech segment aligned to a source word, predict a distribution over the target vocabulary from the averaged encoder states of that segment (applied to all segments, masked or not). On triplet data, obtain source–target word alignments via Moses/GIZA++ with grow-diag-final; on ASR-only pairs, supervise using a bilingual lexical table built from estimated translation probabilities. Train this with a KL-divergence loss at the top encoder layer so upper layers specialize in cross-lingual word mapping, reducing decoder burden and improving ST performance."}]}
